  "why": "The paper enforces both semantic consistency and naturalness across fuzzing iterations. For naturalness it trains a DCGAN Discriminator on the original training set and uses the discriminator score per initial seed as a fidelity threshold to filter mutants (i.e., restricting search to a learned plausible distribution). For semantic consistency it (1) designs mutation rules to preserve semantics (pixel-level mutations on only 0.5% of pixels; image-level mutations applied to whole image to avoid creating unrealistic partial edits), (2) applies the discriminator threshold relative to the original seed (feeding the initial seed into the Discriminator to obtain the per-seed fidelity threshold), and (3) limits cumulative drift via a max_times cap on how often a seed may be mutated and via seed-selection decay to prefer newer seeds. These mechanisms explicitly control realism and semantic similarity relative to the seed across iterations, matching the metric's High criteria.",
